		}
	</script><BR><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><font class="h1font">Extended: Intermediate Decks</font></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tr height="10"><td width="98%" bgcolor="#669933" height="10"><img src="/magic/gfx/trans.gif" width="6" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td><td valign="bottom" align="right"><img src="/magic/gfx/hrz/tg.gif" width="103" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
</tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td valign="top" align="right">
<img src="/magic/gfx/hrz/bg.gif" width="92" height="24" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
</tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td colspan="2"><font class="h1font">New Extended Red Beatdown</font></td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Rating</Font></TD><TD><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size=1>(4.88)</font> | <A HREF="/magic/decks/decks.php?reviews=24765">Read Reviews</A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Author</font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> <A HREF="http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=2061">Adam "Vincent Vega" Beauchamp</A></FONT> <font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=2061&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a></font></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Description</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> This is an extended red deck with a lot of cheap creatures and burn.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Submitted</Font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> August 1, 2002</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Cards</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Creatures - 16<br>
Jackal Pup x4<br>
Mogg Fanatic x4<br>
Goblin Cadet x4<br>
Goblin Patrol x4<br>
<br>
Other Spells - 22<br>
Firebolt x4<br>
Cursed Scroll x4<br>
Volcanic Hammer x4<br>
Browbeat x4<br>
Chimeric Idol x4<br>
Urza&#39;s Rage x2<br>
<br>
Land - 22<br>
Wasteland x4<br>
Barbarian Ring x4<br>
Rishadan Port x2<br>
Mountains x12<br>
<br>
Sideboard <br>
Price of Progress x4<br>
Masticore x4<br>
Powder Keg x4<br>
Pillage x3<br>
<br>
   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> This deck is made to play a creature on turn 1. 12 of the creatures have a power of 2, putting control players on a pretty tight clock. I feel in this deck, because of the lack of decent 2 casting cost creatures, giving up a mana on turn 2 to pay the echo on the patrol is better than playing a 2 mana creature. <br>
<br>
The Chimeric Idols are for getting around some of the anti-red cards, and pro red creatures as well. Plus they are very good in this deck, where you can play all of your cards before you attack if you need to. <br>
<br>
This deck has a pretty good bit of card advantage for a red deck, with Firebolt, Browbeat, and Cursed Scroll giving you a chance to pull ahead of you opponent in that category.<br>
<br>
Browbeat is probably my favorite car in this deck, usually drawing three cards (in most cases the three cards you draw will not deal 5 damage.), but sometimes it will deal the 5, which is pretty devestating. This card may seem like it does not go well with Cursed Scroll, but the cards in this deck are so cheap, it works out okay in the end.<br>
<br>
The land is a bit more varied now because there is no need for excess mountains to cast fieblast. Adding the 4 barbarian rings and the 2 rishadan ports gives me a bit more land control, and a few more direct damage spells (assuming you reach threshold).<br>
<br>
The sideboard is just thrown together right now, but I think Price of Progress is a must, because anybody chosing to run a multi-colored deck will have a few painlands, which is very good for this deck. Price of Progress will speed this process along. Masticore is there for weenie decks (like this one) and decks that will have a lot of red hate, like white. Powder Keg is one of the best ways to stop other powder kegs, because you can just let yours sit on 2, but it does a whole lot more than that as well, helping out against a wide variety of cards and decks. Pillage should be something better, but I couldn&#39;t think of anything.<br>
<br>
Thanks for looking,<br>
Adam &#39;Vincent Vega&#39; Beauchamp </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/magic/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/magic/decks/decks.php?reviews=24765"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=24765" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/magic/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font><BR></td></tr></table> <!-- #EndEditable --></td>
